ORIGINAL DESIGNS AND CONCEPTS
================================================================================

The following designs, features, and UI/UX patterns were originated by the
EchoBird project. The source code that implements them is governed by the
AGPL-3.0 license; the *underlying ideas, interface arrangements, and
combinations* are documented here for two reasons:
  (a) so honest downstream forks and reimplementations can credit prior
      art appropriately, and
  (b) to establish a documented priority claim — including specific UI
      creative points and first-use evidence — for any future trade-dress
      or look-and-feel dispute. We list creative points individually so
      it is clear which elements are claimed; the COMBINED TRADE DRESS
      NOTICE further below addresses how the combination of these
      elements is itself protectable.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A. USER-INTERFACE TRADE DRESS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The four entries below are claimed as the distinctive user-interface
"look and feel" of EchoBird. Each entry lists (1) the originating concept
and (2) specific UI creative points that define the pattern, plus
(3) first-public-commit evidence for priority.

  1. Mother Agent (internal codename) / 安装与修复 (user-facing UI name)

     Concept — An autonomous AI agent embedded as a first-class top-level
     surface inside a desktop application, whose ENTIRE PURPOSE is
     installing, repairing, and deploying OTHER agents and AI tools.
     Any AI agent can technically install software; what is original to
     EchoBird is packaging this capability as its own dedicated user-
     facing product surface rather than burying it inside a settings or
     "advanced" page.

     Specific UI creative points:
       - Independent top-level navigation entry (not nested under any
         tool's own settings)
       - Conversational installation flow (not a step-wizard, not a
         checkbox list, not a CLI prompt)
       - Local-execution and remote-execution targets unified under the
         same chat surface (one conversation, two back-end execution
         paths chosen contextually)
       - Persona-style framing of the deployment agent (avatar, name,
         dialog tone) rather than a faceless task runner

     First public commit: 2026-03-02 (src/pages/MotherAgent.tsx, 1410
     lines at commit 546a14ae).

  2. Model Nexus / 模型中心 — "Configure once, used everywhere"

     Concept — A central pool of model configurations (API key, base URL,
     model ID, protocol) presented as a navigable list, structurally
     positioned as the single data source that every other user-facing
     scenario draws from. Configuring a model once in this pool causes it
     to be available across Install & Repair, Local LLM, My AI Projects,
     and App Manager without any per-scenario re-entry of credentials.

     Specific UI creative points:
       - Two-column layout: main list of all model cards on the left;
         per-model detail/edit panel on the right
       - The model list is structurally a "pool" consumed by other
         scenarios — not a settings sub-page subordinate to any one tool
       - Right-edge inline "+" shortcut button for quick-add (not a
         toolbar-top button)
       - Inline one-click latency-test ("ping") before commit, embedded
         on each model card
       - Clicking a card opens the detail/edit view in the same right
         panel (no modal, no page navigation)

     First public commit: 2026-03-02 (initial model directory in
     docs/api/store/models.json and icon set at commit 546a14ae);
     dedicated "Model Nexus" naming: 2026-03-26 (commit 1ae49436);
     full page extraction at commit d80030aa (2026-03-29).

  3. App Manager + My AI Projects (shared UI container)

     Concept — A unified card-grid + right-side-detail container
     that presents two distinct entity types — (a) official AI / Agent
     applications and games and (b) the user's own vibe-coded
     applications and games — through the same UI surface, so the user's
     own projects sit visually alongside official tools as first-class
     citizens. The right-side panel handles model selection and one-click
     "apply" for the selected entity, regardless of which type.

     Specific UI creative points:
       - Card-grid main area + right-side detail panel two-column layout
       - One card = one tool or one user project; all actions for that
         entity (launch / select model / apply / configure) collapse
         into the card-plus-right-panel pair
       - The same ToolCard component renders both official tools and
         user-defined Vibe-Coded projects (MyProjects.tsx imports and
         reuses the AppManager card)
       - Right panel "select model → one-click apply" linear flow
         (no submit button confusion, no separate save state)
       - Per-card "restore to official" affordance as the first row of
         the model list

     First public commits: AppManager — 2026-03-02 (src/pages/
     AppManager.tsx, 674 lines at commit 546a14ae); MyProjects —
     2026-05-20 (src/pages/MyProjects/ at commit 05a35d13).

     Critical: the *bundled reference applications* (Reversi + AI
     Translator) — which form the user-tutorial pattern detailed
     separately in TRADEMARKS.md §4 — were ALREADY PRESENT in the
     same initial commit 546a14ae on 2026-03-02. They were not
     introduced when MyProjects shipped on 2026-05-20; MyProjects
     merely re-positioned the already-existing reference apps from
     "internal built-in tools" to "user-editable templates". Both
     reference applications are intentionally model-bound — they
     cannot function without a model connection from EchoBird's
     central Model Nexus. The architectural intent to guide users
     in building their own *model-bound* AI applications and AI
     games (rather than generic vibe-coded apps that happen to be
     in this folder) was therefore present from day one of
     EchoBird's public release.

  4. LocalServer / 一键本地大模型 — One-click local LLM deployment

     Concept — A desktop-embedded UI that compresses the otherwise
     terminal-heavy process of installing a Python environment,
     downloading a model weight, picking quantization, configuring a
     runtime, and exposing OpenAI-compatible + Anthropic-compatible
     endpoints into a single page with a START button. The point of
     originality is the pairing of multiple LLM runtimes side-by-side
     under one UI, with all the surrounding deployment friction hidden.

     Specific UI creative points:
       - Three runtime engines presented as parallel options under one
         picker (vLLM / SGLang / llama.cpp) — not a single-engine app
         with the others as plugins
       - GPU detection surfaced as a UI element (not a hidden
         auto-config), with the detected backend visible to the user
       - Runtime-aware parameter adaptation: switching engine auto-locks
         "GPU Full / GPU Auto" compute selection to the engine's
         constraints (vLLM / SGLang lock to GPU; llama.cpp keeps the
         full GPU/CPU spectrum)
       - A single "START" button that simultaneously brings up the
         OpenAI-compatible endpoint AND the Anthropic-compatible
         endpoint from the same model weight
       - Quantization picker integrated with model download flow on the
         same page (no separate "downloads" tab)

     First public commit: 2026-03-02 (src/pages/LocalServer.tsx, 1102
     lines at commit 546a14ae).

